(531, 1, '2015-01-26 22:12:43', '2015-01-26 22:12:43', 'The Pointers are three large illuminated arrows mounted on articulating arms against a wall.\r\n\r\nParticipants are invited to point and rotate the arrows as desired, allowing the audience to impact the art changes the perceived impact. They appear to display different messages and emotional reactions when all three are pointed down, or up, or at the gallery attendant to the left. The artistic intention, however, remains the same - that by impacting the art you have more of a connection to your community than just being a passive observer.', 'The Pointers', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '80-revision-v1', '', '', '2015-01-26 22:12:43', '2015-01-26 22:12:43', '', 80, 'http://jenlewinstudio.com/80-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(534, 1, '2015-01-26 22:14:23', '2015-01-26 22:14:23', '<a title="Lenfest Plaza" href="http://www.pafa.org/About/Lenfest-Plaza/743/" target="_blank">Lenfest Plaza:</a> Philadelphia, Pennsylvania\n\nThe Paint Torch is a permanent outdoor sculpture by Claes Oldenburg.\n\nIn 2010, Oldenburg and I met to discuss ways to elegantly incorporate technology and illumination within his proposed piece The Paint Torch.  He had been inspired by some of my art work in particular several FRP illuminated pieces I created with <a title="Kreysler and Associates" href="http://kreysler.com/" target="_blank">Kreysler and Associates</a> in California.   We began working together almost immediately, spending over 12 months developing the sublet, yet elegant internal ‘glow’ you now see within the piece.\n\n<a title="Claes Oldenburg" href="http://oldenburgvanbruggen.com/" target="_blank">Claes Oldenburg</a>    |    Jen Lewin', 'The Paint Torch', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '76-autosave-v1', '', '', '2015-01-26 22:14:23', '2015-01-26 22:14:23', '', 76, 'http://jenlewinstudio.com/76-autosave-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
